<h2><a name="min" id="min">min</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;algorithm&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">const</span> TYPE<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> min<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">const</span> TYPE<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> x<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">const</span> TYPE<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> y <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;
    <span class="kw4">const</span> TYPE<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> min<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">const</span> TYPE<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> x<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">const</span> TYPE<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> y<span class="sy0">,</span> BinPred p <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;</pre>
<p>
The min() function, unsurprisingly, returns the smaller of x and y.
</p>

<p>
By default, the &lt; operator is used to compare the two elements. If the binary
predicate p is given, it will be used instead.
</p>

<p>
